{"title_page": "Bar-Ilan University", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Bar-Ilan}}\n{{short description|Public university in Ramat Gan, Israel}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Bar-Ilan University\n|motto           = Tradition of Excellence\n|native_name     = {{native name|he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d1\u05e8-\u05d0\u05d9\u05dc\u05df}}\n|image           = Bar Ilan seal.svg\n|image_size      = 150px\n|established     = 1955\n|type            = [[Public university|Public]] [[research university|research]]\n|endowment       =\n|faculty         =\n|president       = [[Arie Zaban]]\n|staff           = 1,250\n<!--|administration  = 1,192-->\n|principal       = Zohar Yinon\n|rector          = Miriam Faust\n|chancellor      =\n|vice_chancellor =\n|dean            =\n|head_label      = [[Vice-President]]s\n|head            = Moshe Lewenstein<br />Shulamit Michaeli<br  />Sharon Goldman\n|students        = 18,000\n|doctoral        = 1,000+\n|nickname        = BIU\n|colors          = Grey, Orange, and White\n|city            = [[Ramat Gan]]\n|country         = [[Israel]]\n|campus          = Urban\n|free_label      =\n|free            =\n|website         = [http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php www.biu.ac.il]\n|logo            = [[Image:Bar Ilan logo2.svg|225px]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|32|4|4|N|34|50|33|E|source:hewiki_region:IL_type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n}}\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| QS_W = 551-560\n| ARWU_NU = 5\u20136\n| ARWU_W = 401\u2013500\n| THES_W = 501\u2013600\n}}\n'''Bar-Ilan University''' ('''BIU''', {{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d1\u05e8-\u05d0\u05d9\u05dc\u05df}}, ''Universitat Bar-Ilan'') is a public [[research university]] in the city of [[Ramat Gan]] in the [[Tel Aviv District]], [[Israel]]. Established in 1955, Bar Ilan is Israel's second-largest academic institution. It has 18,000 students and 1,350 [[Faculty (university)|faculty]] members.\n\nThe university aims to \"blend tradition with modern technologies and scholarship, and teach the compelling ethics of Jewish heritage to all \u2026 to synthesize the ancient and modern, the sacred and the material, the spiritual and the scientific\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biu.ac.il/General/mission.html |title=Bar-Ilan Mission |publisher=Biu.ac.il |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:First Graduation at Bar Ilan University - Ogden Reid 1959.jpg|thumb|150px|First Bar-Ilan graduation, 1959]]\n[[File:\u05d4\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05dc\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05e6\u05e4\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d1 \u05d4\u05e7\u05de\u05e4\u05d5\u05e1 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05d5\u05e0\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9 (11562183273).jpg|thumb|Wengerovsky Center at Bar-Ilan University]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 15922 Unity park in Bar-Ilan University.JPG|thumb|Bar-Ilan Faculty of engineering]]\n[[File:\u05d1\u05e0\u05d9\u05df \u05e4\u05e1\u05d9\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05d0\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d5\u05de\u05e7\u05e1 \u05d5\u05d5\u05d1 \u05d5\u05de\u05e9\u05e4\u05d7\u05ea\u05dd (11795059335).jpg|thumb|Psychology building in Bar-Ilan University]]\n[[File:Bar-Ilan Faculty of Medicine in the Galilee 01.JPG|thumb|Bar-Ilan Faculty of Medicine]]\n[[File:Brain research labs-Bar Ilan university.jpg|thumb|Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center at Bar-Ilan University]]\n[[File:\u05d4\u05d8\u05e8\u05d9\u05e4\u05dc\u05e7\u05e1 \u05dc\u05e0\u05e0\u05d5\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05dc\u05e1\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d5\u05e1\u05d5\u05d6\u05df \u05d2\u05d5\u05e0\u05d3\u05d4 \u05d2\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05e9\u05de\u05d9\u05d3 (11513855913).jpg|thumb|Nanotechnology building]]\n[[File:\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05e5 - \u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05e1\u05de\u05d9 \u05e9\u05de\u05e2\u05d5\u05df \u05dc\u05dc\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e4\u05d9\u05dc\u05d5\u05e1\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05ea\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 \u05d5\u05de\u05d7\u05e9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc (11908099463).jpg|thumb|Centre for the study of philosophy ethics and Jewish thought]]\n\nBar-Ilan University has Jewish-American roots: It was conceived in [[Atlanta]] in a meeting of the American Mizrahi organization in 1950, and was founded by Professor [[Pinkhos Churgin]], an American [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] [[rabbi]] and educator, who was president from 1955 to 1957 where he was succeeded by [[Joseph H. Lookstein]] who was president from 1957 to 1967.<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=6551&pt=1&pid=988&level=5&cPath=35,983,988 |title=Bar-Ilan Presidents &#124; Bar Ilan University |publisher=.biu.ac.il |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> When it was opened in 1955, it was described by The New York Times \"as Cultural Link Between the [Israeli] Republic and America\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biu.ac.il/General/biu_history.html |title=Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biu.ac.il |date=May 10, 1955 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> The university was named for Rabbi [[Meir Bar-Ilan]] (originally ''Meir Berlin''), a [[Religious Zionist]] leader who served as the inspiration for its establishment. Although he was trained in Orthodox seminaries in Berlin, he believed there was a need for an institution providing a dual curriculum of secular [[academic]] studies and religious [[Torah]] studies.\n\nThe founders of the university hoped to produce [[alumni]] committed to Jewish religious tradition, Zionist ideology, and science. In 1965, the professors and lecturers were all religious Jews, as were the majority of students. [[Yosef Burg]], one of the prominent leaders of the [[religious Zionist movement]], warned that admission of too many non-religious into the university could undermine its character: \"If you spill too much water into a wine bottle, you will have no wine.\" Today, the student population includes secular and non-Jewish students, including [[Arab]]s. Seven courses in [[Jewish studies]] are required for graduation. In hiring senior academic staff, the university used to give preference to religious Jews,{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} although this is no longer true, and the faculty includes many secular Jewish members, and also Arab faculty, such as Dr. Totry - Jubran Manal at the law faculty. Presidents who followed were [[Max Jammer]] (1967\u201377), [[Emanuel Rackman]] (1977\u201386), [[Michael Albeck]] (1986\u201389), [[Ernest Krausz]] (1989), [[Zvi Arad]] (1989\u201392), and [[Shlomo Eckstein]] (1992-96).<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\"/>\n\n[[Yitzhak Rabin|Yitzhak Rabin's]] convicted assassin, [[Yigal Amir]], was a student of law and computer science at Bar-Ilan, prompting charges that the university had become a hotbed of political [[extremism]]. One of the steps taken by the university following the 1995 assassination was to encourage dialogue between [[Israeli left-wing politics|left-wing]] and [[Israeli right-wing politics|right-wing]] students.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wagner|first=Matthew|title=Bar-Ilan again forced to deal with the extremists in its midst|url=http://www.jpost.com/LandedPages/PrintArticle.aspx?id=72376|work=Jerusalem Post|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kalman|first=Matthew|title=A Bitter Return to Politics at Israel's Bar-Ilan U.|url=http://chronicle.com/article/A-Bitter-Return-to-Politics-at/127097/|work=Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nUnder university president [[Moshe Kaveh]] (1996-2013), Bar-Ilan underwent a major expansion, with new buildings added on the northern side of the [[campus]]. New science programs have been introduced, including an multidisciplinary brain research center <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biu.ac.il/interdis/gondabrain/index_eng.html |title=Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center, Bar Ilan University |publisher=Biu.ac.il |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> and a center for [[nanotechnology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nanocenter.biu.ac.il/php/general/first.php |title=Center for Advanced Materials and Nanotechnology. Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Nanocenter.biu.ac.il |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721170333/http://www.nanocenter.biu.ac.il/php/general/first.php |archivedate=July 21, 2011 }}</ref> The university has placed [[archaeology]] as one of its priorities, and this includes excavations such as the Tell es-Safi/Gath archaeological excavations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dig-gath.org |title=The Tell es-Safi/Gath Archaeological Project |publisher=Dig-gath.org |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> and the recently opened Bar-Ilan University/[[Weizmann Institute of Science]] joint program in Archaeological Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kimmel Center for Archaeological Science |url=http://www.weizmann.ac.il/kimmel-arch/iuprogram.html |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829161256/http://www.weizmann.ac.il/kimmel-arch/iuprogram.html |archivedate=August 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBar-Ilan's Faculty of Law made headlines in 2008 by achieving the highest average Israeli Bar Exam grade of 81.9 by its graduates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelbar.org.il/uploadFiles/statistica%20may%202008.pdf |title=Results of the Bar Exam 5.5.08 (Hebrew) |format=PDF|publisher=Israelbar.org.il |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> [[Daniel Hershkowitz]] was university President from 2013 to 2017.<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\"/>\n\nDuring [[Operation Protective Edge]] in 2014, the university allowed 30 of Dr. Uri Weiss\u2019 students to switch out of his course after they accused him of being an extreme leftist and said they didn\u2019t want to study with him.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skop |first1=Yarden |title=Israeli University Reneges on Letting Students Skip Settler Critic's Exam |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-university-reneges-on-letting-students-skip-settler-critic-s-exam-1.5409886 |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=Haaretz |date=14 July 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the university became the center of controversy over [[women's rights]]. The university announced it would allow women to read passages of text and play musical instruments at its [[Holocaust Remembrance Day]], but would bar women from singing in order not to offend Orthodox Jewish males. Other organizations, such as Ne'emanei Torah V'Avodah, protested that it is an Israeli custom to sing at national ceremonies, and that \"extreme\" Jewish religious law should not be imposed on the general public.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Bar-Ilan-Univ-bans-women-singing-in-memorial-ceremony-453021 Bar-Ilan Univ. bans women singing in memorial ceremony] The Jerusalem Post, May 4, 2016</ref>\n\nBar-Ilan operates a [[kollel]] for men and a [[midrasha]] for women. The kollel offers traditional [[yeshiva]] studies with an emphasis on [[Talmud]], while the midrasha offers courses in [[Torah]] and [[Jewish philosophy]]. These programs are open to all students free of charge.\n\n[[Arie Zaban]] became the President of the university in 2017.<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\"/>\n\n==Academics==\nBar-Ilan University has eight faculties: [[Exact Sciences]], [[Life Sciences]], [[Social Sciences]], [[Humanities]], [[Jewish Studies]], [[Medicine]], [[Engineering]], and [[Law]]. There are also interdisciplinary studies.\n\n=== Programs of study ===\n\nThe center's mission is to cultivate a new generation of interdisciplinary scientists who integrate knowledge from different fields. The center offers several graduate level tracks, including a direct Ph.D. program, an M.Sc. program, and a combined program. Candidates are accepted from a variety of backgrounds, including biology, psychology, mathematics, physics, and computer science. Accepted students are exempt from tuition and receive a full scholarship during the course of their studies, allowing to fully concentrate on the research.\n\nThe Ph.D. training program builds on six single-semester required core courses, a set of preparatory courses, and a variety of elective courses. Students have to complete 8 credits in advanced courses. Additionally, students participate in a number of multidisciplinary activities including a weekly research seminar and two hands-on short-term research projects. Several advanced optional courses are available, allowing students to specialize in one of the three sub-fields:\n\n1. Computational Neuroscience\n\n2. Neurobiology and Behavior\n\n3. Language and Cognition\n\nThe center also offers an undergraduate interdisciplinary program in neuroscience, providing a solid knowledge base in wide range of neuroscience related disciplines, such as life sciences, psychology, linguistics, mathematics and computer sciences, and physics, with a specialization in the field of choice.\n\nThe center takes part in the summer science research internship program, where undergraduate science majors from American universities perform research internships in Bar-Ilan labs under the mentorship of faculty members.\n\n===Special programs===\nBar-Ilan offers an International B.A. Program,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biuinternational.com |title=International B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University &#124; Israel's premier university for Olim and Overseas students!International B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University &#124; Israel's premier university for Olim and Overseas students! |publisher=Biuinternational.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> taught entirely in [[English language|English]], and is the first university in Israel to offer a full undergraduate program taught entirely in English. Currently students can choose between a B.A. degree in interdisciplinary social sciences,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/ |title=Interdisciplinary Social Sciences - BIU InternationalInternational B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biuinternational.com |accessdate=2013-10-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101121215/http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/ |archive-date=2013-11-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> where students can choose between a macro track in economics, political sciences, and sociology,<ref name=\"biuinternational1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/tracks |title=Academic Tracks in the Social Sciences - BIU InternationalInternational B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biuinternational.com |accessdate=2013-10-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103115146/http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/tracks/ |archive-date=2013-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> or the Micro Track in Criminology, Psychology, and Sociology,<ref name=\"biuinternational1\"/> or a major in communications,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/communication |title=International B.A. Program in Communication - BIU InternationalInternational B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biuinternational.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> with a minor in either [[English literature]] or [[political science]]. The degrees are internationally recognized and are open to students from all over the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.biu.ac.il |title=Bar-Ilan University |publisher=BIU |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bar-Ilan offers a preparatory program that readies [[aliyah|new immigrants]] for [[Israel]]i colleges. The university also runs a one-year overseas program called Tochnit [[Torah im Derech Eretz|Torah Im Derech Eretz]], which combines traditional [[kollel]] [[Torah]] studies in the morning, separate for men and women, as well as co-ed general university studies and [[Jewish history]] classes in the afternoon. Many American students enrolled in regular programs of study in the university also take these Jewish history classes to fulfill their [[Jewish studies]] requirements.\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nBar-Ilan's on-line [[responsa]] project was awarded the [[Israel Prize]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.digento.de/titel/105616.html |title=The Bar Ilan Responsa Project (Global Jewish Database) |publisher=Digento.de |date=November 18, 2002 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> The university's Bible project, in danger of being eliminated by continued budget cuts, was saved at the last minute by an anonymous donor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ilani |first=Ofri |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/795573.html |title=Bar-Ilan University Bible project |publisher=Haaretz.com |date=April 2, 2008 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn its capacity as a business school, Bar-Ilan was placed as the 4th best business school in Africa and the Middle East in the 2010 [[QS Global 200 Business Schools Report]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topmba.com/mba-rankings/top-business-schools-report-2010/regions/top-business-schools-in-africa-and-middle-east |title=Top Business Schools |publisher=TopMBA.com |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Leslie and Susan Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center ==\nThe Leslie and Susan Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center (Hebrew: \u05d4\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05ea\u05d7\u05d5\u05de\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d7\u05e7\u05e8 \u05d4\u05de\u05d5\u05d7 \u05e2\u2033\u05e9 \u05dc\u05e1\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d5\u05e1\u05d5\u05d6\u05df \u05d2\u05d5\u05e0\u05d3\u05d4) focuses on a multidisciplinary approach to neuroscience. It houses over 30 laboratories investigating brain complexity at multiple levels, from single [[neuron]]s, through information processing and computations in neural networks to cognition, behavior and human mind. The center's core members and affiliates combine multiple fields that are crucial for brain understanding, including molecular and systems neuroscience, cognitive neuroscience, psychology, psychiatry, linguistics, mathematics, computer sciences, engineering and physics. Numerous research approaches are employed by the center's scientists, such as brain stimulation techniques, neuroimaging, electrophysiology, molecular techniques, computational methods, mathematical modeling and behavioral and cognitive paradigms. The center was founded in 2002 thanks to the contributions of the Gonda family, the president of Bar-Ilan University Moshe Kaveh, and [[Moshe Abeles]], a pioneer of Israel's neuroscience research, [[The EMET Prize for Art, Science and Culture|Emet Prize]] laureate (2004) and the founding director of the [[Interdisciplinary Center for Neural Computation]] at the Hebrew University (1992\u20131999), has led the Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center for nearly a decade. Since 2011, the center is headed by [[Moshe Bar (neuroscientist)|Moshe Bar]], a cognitive neuroscientist and an expert in brain imaging technologies. Bar returned to Israel to head the Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center as its new director after thirteen years at Harvard University.\n\n=== Magnetoencephalography ===\n\nThe Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center hosts the only [[magnetoencephalography]] facility in Israel, operated by the Electromagnetic Brain Imaging Unit established in 2008. Magnetoencephalography is a brain imaging technique that allows studying human brain responses by measuring the magnetic fields produced by electrical brain activity at superb (millisecond) temporal resolution. The unit is headed by Professor Abraham Goldstein. It is equipped with a 248 [[magnetometer]] sensors whole-head system, positioned inside a double-wall magnetically shielded room by IMEDCO. Once a week, magnetoencephalography is dedicated to serving the community by providing clinical and diagnostic services, such as localization of epileptic foci, via BrainMap.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{see also|Category:Bar-Ilan University alumni}}\n[[File:Gila Gamliel.jpg|thumb|80px|[[Gila Gamliel]]]]\n[[File:Tzipi Livni 2.JPG|thumb|80px|[[Tzipi Livni]]]]\n[[File:Ami Ayalon.jpg|thumb|80px|[[Ami Ayalon]]]] \n* [[Zvi Arad]] (1942-2018) - mathematician, acting President of Bar-Ilan University, President of [[Netanya Academic College]]\n* [[Ami Ayalon]] - Former head of the [[Shin Bet]] and member of the [[Knesset]] for the [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]].\n* [[Michael Ben-Ari]] - Israeli politician and formerly a member of the Knesset for the [[National Union (Israel)|National Union Party]].\n* [[Kotel Da-Don]] - Croatian [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] rabbi of the Bet Israel community in Zagreb.\n* [[Avi Dichter]] - current Minister of Home Front Defence. Former [[Shin Bet]] director.\n* [[Yuval Diskin]] - 12th Director of the Israeli Internal Security Service [[Shin Bet]].\n* [[Esther Farbstein]] - Holocaust scholar\n* [[Gila Gamliel]] - Israeli politician for the [[Likud Party]]\n* [[Michael Harris (academic)|Michael Harris]] - named the best Israeli in the field of academics, as one of \"The 10 Most Successful Israelis in 10 Different Fields in the World\" by ''[[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]]'' in April 2012.<ref>[http://www.iuk.edu/chancellor/assets/pdf/Maarivarticle.pdf]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Klafter]] - [[chemical physics]] professor, the eighth President of Tel Aviv University\n* [[Joshua Kulp]] - Talmudic scholar\n* [[Norman Lebrecht]] (born 1948) - British commentator on music and cultural affairs, and novelist\n* [[Tzipi Livni]] - Israeli lawyer and politician, head of the Opposition from 2009-2012. Former Minister of Justice and in charge of negotiations with the Palestinians\n* [[Gadeer Mreeh]] (born 1984) - first [[Druze]] woman to become a member of the [[Knesset]]\n* [[Avi Weinroth]] - Lawyer represents corporations in Israel and governmental companies.\n\n==Notable faculty==\n{{see also|Category:Bar-Ilan University faculty}}\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Doron Aurbach]]\n* [[Nathan Aviezer]]\n* [[Moshe Bar (neuroscientist)|Moshe Bar]]\n* [[Avi Bell]]\n*[[Pinkhos Churgin]] \n* [[Cyril Domb]]\n* [[Shlomo Eckstein]]\n* [[Adam Ferziger]]\n* [[Jonathan Fox (professor of politics)|Jonathan Fox]]\n* [[Hillel Furstenberg]]\n* [[Ruth Halperin-Kaddari]]\n* [[Oren Harman]]\n* [[Shlomo Havlin]]\n* [[Arye L. Hillman]]\n* [[Max Jammer]]\n* [[Efraim Karsh]]\n* [[Mordechai Kedar]]\n* [[Sarit Kraus]]\n* [[Ernest Krausz]]\n* [[Baruch Kurzweil]]\n* [[Aren Maeir]]\n* [[Arie Reich]]\n* [[Mary Schaps]]\n* [[Daniel Sperber]]\n* [[Avraham Trahtman]]\n* [[Zeev Zalevsky]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Israel]]\n* [[Ashkelon Academic College]]\n* [[Jerusalem College of Technology]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.biu.ac.il/index_eng.shtml}}\n* [http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=980&pt=1&pid=35&level=3&cPath=35,980 BIU History]\n* [http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=90&pt=4&pid=30&level=2&cPath=90 Bar-Ilan University \u2013 Study Programs for Olim/Foreign Students]\n* [http://www.judaismshop.com/Bar-Ilan-Responsa/ Bar-Ilan responsa website]\n* [http://medicine.biu.ac.il/en Bar-Ilan Faculty of Medicine]\n* [http://nano.biu.ac.il/ Bar-Ilan Institute of Nanotechnology and Advanced Materials (BINA)]\n* [http://law.biu.ac.il/en Bar-Ilan Faculty of Law]\n* {{in lang|he}} [http://www.bis.org.il Bar-Ilan Students Union]\n* {{in lang|es}} [http://www.alubi.org Amigos Latinoamericanos de la Universidad de Bar Ilan]\n\n{{Universities in Israel}}\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Religious Zionism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University| ]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1955]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ramat Gan]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Israel]]\n[[Category:Universities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Education in Tel Aviv District]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public university in Ramat Gan, Israel}}\n{{Redirect|Bar-Ilan}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name            = Bar-Ilan University\n|motto           = Tradition of Excellence\n|native_name     = {{native name|he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d1\u05e8-\u05d0\u05d9\u05dc\u05df}}\n|image           = Bar Ilan seal.svg\n|image_size      = 150px\n|established     = 1955\n|type            = [[Public university|Public]] [[research university|research]]\n|endowment       =\n|faculty         =\n|president       = [[Arie Zaban]]\n|staff           = 1,250\n<!--|administration  = 1,192-->\n|principal       = Zohar Yinon\n|rector          = Miriam Faust\n|chancellor      =\n|vice_chancellor =\n|dean            =\n|head_label      = [[Vice-President]]s\n|head            = Moshe Lewenstein<br />Shulamit Michaeli<br  />Sharon Goldman\n|students        = 18,000\n|doctoral        = 1,000+\n|nickname        = BIU\n|colors          = Grey, Orange, and White\n|city            = [[Ramat Gan]]\n|country         = [[Israel]]\n|campus          = Urban\n|free_label      =\n|free            =\n|website         = [http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php www.biu.ac.il]\n|logo            = [[Image:Bar Ilan logo2.svg|225px]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|32|4|4|N|34|50|33|E|source:hewiki_region:IL_type:edu|display=title,inline}}\n}}\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| QS_W = 551-560\n| ARWU_NU = 5\u20136\n| ARWU_W = 401\u2013500\n| THES_W = 501\u2013600\n}}\n'''Bar-Ilan University''' ('''BIU''', {{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d1\u05e8-\u05d0\u05d9\u05dc\u05df}}, ''Universitat Bar-Ilan'') is a public [[research university]] in the city of [[Ramat Gan]] in the [[Tel Aviv District]], [[Israel]]. Established in 1955, Bar Ilan is Israel's second-largest academic institution. It has 18,000 students and 1,350 [[Faculty (university)|faculty]] members.\n\nThe university aims to \"blend tradition with modern technologies and scholarship, and teach the compelling ethics of Jewish heritage to all \u2026 to synthesize the ancient and modern, the sacred and the material, the spiritual and the scientific\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biu.ac.il/General/mission.html |title=Bar-Ilan Mission |publisher=Biu.ac.il |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:First Graduation at Bar Ilan University - Ogden Reid 1959.jpg|thumb|150px|First Bar-Ilan graduation, 1959]]\n[[File:\u05d4\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05dc\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05e6\u05e4\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d1 \u05d4\u05e7\u05de\u05e4\u05d5\u05e1 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05d5\u05e0\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05e1\u05e7\u05d9 (11562183273).jpg|thumb|Wengerovsky Center at Bar-Ilan University]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 15922 Unity park in Bar-Ilan University.JPG|thumb|Bar-Ilan Faculty of engineering]]\n[[File:\u05d1\u05e0\u05d9\u05df \u05e4\u05e1\u05d9\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05d0\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d5\u05de\u05e7\u05e1 \u05d5\u05d5\u05d1 \u05d5\u05de\u05e9\u05e4\u05d7\u05ea\u05dd (11795059335).jpg|thumb|Psychology building in Bar-Ilan University]]\n[[File:Bar-Ilan Faculty of Medicine in the Galilee 01.JPG|thumb|Bar-Ilan Faculty of Medicine]]\n[[File:Brain research labs-Bar Ilan university.jpg|thumb|Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center at Bar-Ilan University]]\n[[File:\u05d4\u05d8\u05e8\u05d9\u05e4\u05dc\u05e7\u05e1 \u05dc\u05e0\u05e0\u05d5\u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e2\"\u05e9 \u05dc\u05e1\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d5\u05e1\u05d5\u05d6\u05df \u05d2\u05d5\u05e0\u05d3\u05d4 \u05d2\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05e9\u05de\u05d9\u05d3 (11513855913).jpg|thumb|Nanotechnology building]]\n[[File:\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05e5 - \u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05e1\u05de\u05d9 \u05e9\u05de\u05e2\u05d5\u05df \u05dc\u05dc\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e4\u05d9\u05dc\u05d5\u05e1\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05ea\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 \u05d5\u05de\u05d7\u05e9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc (11908099463).jpg|thumb|Centre for the study of philosophy ethics and Jewish thought]]\n\nBar-Ilan University has Jewish-American roots: It was conceived in [[Atlanta]] in a meeting of the American Mizrahi organization in 1950, and was founded by Professor [[Pinkhos Churgin]], an American [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] [[rabbi]] and educator, who was president from 1955 to 1957 where he was succeeded by [[Joseph H. Lookstein]] who was president from 1957 to 1967.<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=6551&pt=1&pid=988&level=5&cPath=35,983,988 |title=Bar-Ilan Presidents &#124; Bar Ilan University |publisher=.biu.ac.il |date= |accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> When it was opened in 1955, it was described by The New York Times \"as Cultural Link Between the [Israeli] Republic and America\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biu.ac.il/General/biu_history.html |title=Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biu.ac.il |date=May 10, 1955 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> The university was named for Rabbi [[Meir Bar-Ilan]] (originally ''Meir Berlin''), a [[Religious Zionist]] leader who served as the inspiration for its establishment. Although he was trained in Orthodox seminaries in Berlin, he believed there was a need for an institution providing a dual curriculum of secular [[academic]] studies and religious [[Torah]] studies.\n\nThe founders of the university hoped to produce [[alumni]] committed to Jewish religious tradition, Zionist ideology, and science. In 1965, the professors and lecturers were all religious Jews, as were the majority of students. [[Yosef Burg]], one of the prominent leaders of the [[religious Zionist movement]], warned that admission of too many non-religious into the university could undermine its character: \"If you spill too much water into a wine bottle, you will have no wine.\" Today, the student population includes secular and non-Jewish students, including [[Arab]]s. Seven courses in [[Jewish studies]] are required for graduation. In hiring senior academic staff, the university used to give preference to religious Jews,{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} although this is no longer true, and the faculty includes many secular Jewish members, and also Arab faculty, such as Dr. Totry - Jubran Manal at the law faculty. Presidents who followed were [[Max Jammer]] (1967-77), [[Emanuel Rackman]] (1977-86), [[Michael Albeck]] (1986-89), [[Ernest Krausz]] (1989), [[Zvi Arad]] (1989-92), and [[Shlomo Eckstein]] (1992-96).<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\"/>\n\n[[Yitzhak Rabin|Yitzhak Rabin's]] convicted assassin, [[Yigal Amir]], was a student of law and computer science at Bar-Ilan, prompting charges that the university had become a hotbed of political [[extremism]]. One of the steps taken by the university following the 1995 assassination was to encourage dialogue between [[Israeli left-wing politics|left-wing]] and [[Israeli right-wing politics|right-wing]] students.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wagner|first=Matthew|title=Bar-Ilan again forced to deal with the extremists in its midst|url=http://www.jpost.com/LandedPages/PrintArticle.aspx?id=72376|work=Jerusalem Post|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kalman|first=Matthew|title=A Bitter Return to Politics at Israel's Bar-Ilan U.|url=http://chronicle.com/article/A-Bitter-Return-to-Politics-at/127097/|work=Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nUnder university president [[Moshe Kaveh]] (1996-2013), Bar-Ilan underwent a major expansion, with new buildings added on the northern side of the [[campus]]. New science programs have been introduced, including an multidisciplinary brain research center <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biu.ac.il/interdis/gondabrain/index_eng.html |title=Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center, Bar Ilan University |publisher=Biu.ac.il |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> and a center for [[nanotechnology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nanocenter.biu.ac.il/php/general/first.php |title=Center for Advanced Materials and Nanotechnology. Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Nanocenter.biu.ac.il |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721170333/http://www.nanocenter.biu.ac.il/php/general/first.php |archivedate=July 21, 2011 }}</ref> The university has placed [[archaeology]] as one of its priorities, and this includes excavations such as the Tell es-Safi/Gath archaeological excavations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dig-gath.org |title=The Tell es-Safi/Gath Archaeological Project |publisher=Dig-gath.org |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> and the recently opened Bar-Ilan University/[[Weizmann Institute of Science]] joint program in Archaeological Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kimmel Center for Archaeological Science |url=http://www.weizmann.ac.il/kimmel-arch/iuprogram.html |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829161256/http://www.weizmann.ac.il/kimmel-arch/iuprogram.html |archivedate=August 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBar-Ilan's Faculty of Law made headlines in 2008 by achieving the highest average Israeli Bar Exam grade of 81.9 by its graduates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelbar.org.il/uploadFiles/statistica%20may%202008.pdf |title=Results of the Bar Exam 5.5.08 (Hebrew) |format=PDF|publisher=Israelbar.org.il |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> [[Daniel Hershkowitz]] was university President from 2013 to 2017.<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\"/>\n\nDuring [[Operation Protective Edge]] in 2014, the university allowed 30 of Dr. Uri Weiss\u2019 students to switch out of his course after they accused him of being an extreme leftist and said they didn\u2019t want to study with him.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skop |first1=Yarden |title=Israeli University Reneges on Letting Students Skip Settler Critic's Exam |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-university-reneges-on-letting-students-skip-settler-critic-s-exam-1.5409886 |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=Haaretz |date=14 July 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the university became the center of controversy over [[women's rights]]. The university announced it would allow women to read passages of text and play musical instruments at its [[Holocaust Remembrance Day]], but would bar women from singing in order not to offend Orthodox Jewish males. Other organizations, such as Ne'emanei Torah V'Avodah, protested that it is an Israeli custom to sing at national ceremonies, and that \"extreme\" Jewish religious law should not be imposed on the general public.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Bar-Ilan-Univ-bans-women-singing-in-memorial-ceremony-453021 Bar-Ilan Univ. bans women singing in memorial ceremony] The Jerusalem Post, May 4, 2016</ref>\n\nBar-Ilan operates a [[kollel]] for men and a [[midrasha]] for women. The kollel offers traditional [[yeshiva]] studies with an emphasis on [[Talmud]], while the midrasha offers courses in [[Torah]] and [[Jewish philosophy]]. These programs are open to all students free of charge.\n\n[[Arie Zaban]] became the President of the university in 2017.<ref name=\"autogeneratedil\"/>\n\n==Academics==\nBar-Ilan University has eight faculties: [[Exact Sciences]], [[Life Sciences]], [[Social Sciences]], [[Humanities]], [[Jewish Studies]], [[Medicine]], [[Engineering]], and [[Law]]. There are also interdisciplinary studies.\n\n=== Programs of study ===\n\nThe center's mission is to cultivate a new generation of interdisciplinary scientists who integrate knowledge from different fields. The center offers several graduate level tracks, including a direct Ph.D. program, an M.Sc. program, and a combined program. Candidates are accepted from a variety of backgrounds, including biology, psychology, mathematics, physics, and computer science. Accepted students are exempt from tuition and receive a full scholarship during the course of their studies, allowing to fully concentrate on the research.\n\nThe Ph.D. training program builds on six single-semester required core courses, a set of preparatory courses, and a variety of elective courses. Students have to complete 8 credits in advanced courses. Additionally, students participate in a number of multidisciplinary activities including a weekly research seminar and two hands-on short-term research projects. Several advanced optional courses are available, allowing students to specialize in one of the three sub-fields:\n\n1. Computational Neuroscience\n\n2. Neurobiology and Behavior\n\n3. Language and Cognition\n\nThe center also offers an undergraduate interdisciplinary program in neuroscience, providing a solid knowledge base in wide range of neuroscience related disciplines, such as life sciences, psychology, linguistics, mathematics and computer sciences, and physics, with a specialization in the field of choice.\n\nThe center takes part in the summer science research internship program, where undergraduate science majors from American universities perform research internships in Bar-Ilan labs under the mentorship of faculty members.\n\n===Special programs===\nBar-Ilan offers an International B.A. Program,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biuinternational.com |title=International B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University &#124; Israel's premier university for Olim and Overseas students!International B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University &#124; Israel's premier university for Olim and Overseas students! |publisher=Biuinternational.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> taught entirely in [[English language|English]], and is the first university in Israel to offer a full undergraduate program taught entirely in English. Currently students can choose between a B.A. degree in interdisciplinary social sciences,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/ |title=Interdisciplinary Social Sciences - BIU InternationalInternational B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biuinternational.com |accessdate=2013-10-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101121215/http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/ |archive-date=2013-11-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> where students can choose between a macro track in economics, political sciences, and sociology,<ref name=\"biuinternational1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/tracks |title=Academic Tracks in the Social Sciences - BIU InternationalInternational B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biuinternational.com |accessdate=2013-10-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103115146/http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/social-sciences/tracks/ |archive-date=2013-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> or the Micro Track in Criminology, Psychology, and Sociology,<ref name=\"biuinternational1\"/> or a major in communications,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biuinternational.com/academics/communication |title=International B.A. Program in Communication - BIU InternationalInternational B.A. Programs: Bar-Ilan University |publisher=Biuinternational.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> with a minor in either [[English literature]] or [[political science]]. The degrees are internationally recognized and are open to students from all over the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.biu.ac.il |title=Bar-Ilan University |publisher=BIU |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bar-Ilan offers a preparatory program that readies [[aliyah|new immigrants]] for [[Israel]]i colleges. The university also runs a one-year overseas program called Tochnit [[Torah im Derech Eretz|Torah Im Derech Eretz]], which combines traditional [[kollel]] [[Torah]] studies in the morning, separate for men and women, as well as co-ed general university studies and [[Jewish history]] classes in the afternoon. Many American students enrolled in regular programs of study in the university also take these Jewish history classes to fulfill their [[Jewish studies]] requirements.\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nBar-Ilan's on-line [[responsa]] project was awarded the [[Israel Prize]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.digento.de/titel/105616.html |title=The Bar Ilan Responsa Project (Global Jewish Database) |publisher=Digento.de |date=November 18, 2002 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> The university's Bible project, in danger of being eliminated by continued budget cuts, was saved at the last minute by an anonymous donor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ilani |first=Ofri |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/795573.html |title=Bar-Ilan University Bible project |publisher=Haaretz.com |date=April 2, 2008 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn its capacity as a business school, Bar-Ilan was placed as the 4th best business school in Africa and the Middle East in the 2010 [[QS Global 200 Business Schools Report]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topmba.com/mba-rankings/top-business-schools-report-2010/regions/top-business-schools-in-africa-and-middle-east |title=Top Business Schools |publisher=TopMBA.com |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Leslie and Susan Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center ==\nThe Leslie and Susan Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center (Hebrew: \u05d4\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05ea\u05d7\u05d5\u05de\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d7\u05e7\u05e8 \u05d4\u05de\u05d5\u05d7 \u05e2\u2033\u05e9 \u05dc\u05e1\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d5\u05e1\u05d5\u05d6\u05df \u05d2\u05d5\u05e0\u05d3\u05d4) focuses on a multidisciplinary approach to neuroscience. It houses over 30 laboratories investigating brain complexity at multiple levels, from single [[neuron]]s, through information processing and computations in neural networks to cognition, behavior and human mind. The center's core members and affiliates combine multiple fields that are crucial for brain understanding, including molecular and systems neuroscience, cognitive neuroscience, psychology, psychiatry, linguistics, mathematics, computer sciences, engineering and physics. Numerous research approaches are employed by the center's scientists, such as brain stimulation techniques, neuroimaging, electrophysiology, molecular techniques, computational methods, mathematical modeling and behavioral and cognitive paradigms. The center was founded in 2002 thanks to the contributions of the Gonda family, the president of Bar-Ilan University Moshe Kaveh, and [[Moshe Abeles]], a pioneer of Israel's neuroscience research, [[The EMET Prize for Art, Science and Culture|Emet Prize]] laureate (2004) and the founding director of the [[Interdisciplinary Center for Neural Computation]] at the Hebrew University (1992\u20131999), has led the Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center for nearly a decade. Since 2011, the center is headed by [[Moshe Bar (neuroscientist)|Moshe Bar]], a cognitive neuroscientist and an expert in brain imaging technologies. Bar returned to Israel to head the Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center as its new director after thirteen years at Harvard University.\n\n=== Magnetoencephalography ===\n\nThe Gonda Multidisciplinary Brain Research Center hosts the only [[magnetoencephalography]] facility in Israel, operated by the Electromagnetic Brain Imaging Unit established in 2008. Magnetoencephalography is a brain imaging technique that allows studying human brain responses by measuring the magnetic fields produced by electrical brain activity at superb (millisecond) temporal resolution. The unit is headed by Professor Abraham Goldstein. It is equipped with a 248 [[magnetometer]] sensors whole-head system, positioned inside a double-wall magnetically shielded room by IMEDCO. Once a week, magnetoencephalography is dedicated to serving the community by providing clinical and diagnostic services, such as localization of epileptic foci, via BrainMap.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{see also|Category:Bar-Ilan University alumni}}\n[[File:Gila Gamliel.jpg|thumb|80px|[[Gila Gamliel]]]]\n[[File:Tzipi Livni 2.JPG|thumb|80px|[[Tzipi Livni]]]]\n[[File:Ami Ayalon.jpg|thumb|80px|[[Ami Ayalon]]]] \n* [[Zvi Arad]] (1942-2018) - mathematician, acting President of Bar-Ilan University, President of [[Netanya Academic College]]\n* [[Ami Ayalon]] - Former head of the [[Shin Bet]] and member of the [[Knesset]] for the [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]].\n* [[Michael Ben-Ari]] - Israeli politician and formerly a member of the Knesset for the [[National Union (Israel)|National Union Party]].\n* [[Kotel Da-Don]] - Croatian [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] rabbi of the Bet Israel community in Zagreb.\n* [[Avi Dichter]] - current Minister of Home Front Defence. Former [[Shin Bet]] director.\n* [[Yuval Diskin]] - 12th Director of the Israeli Internal Security Service [[Shin Bet]].\n* [[Esther Farbstein]] - Holocaust scholar\n* [[Gila Gamliel]] - Israeli politician for the [[Likud Party]]\n* [[Michael Harris (academic)|Michael Harris]] - named the best Israeli in the field of academics, as one of \"The 10 Most Successful Israelis in 10 Different Fields in the World\" by ''[[Maariv (newspaper)|Maariv]]'' in April 2012.<ref>[http://www.iuk.edu/chancellor/assets/pdf/Maarivarticle.pdf]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Klafter]] - [[chemical physics]] professor, the eighth President of Tel Aviv University\n* [[Joshua Kulp]] - Talmudic scholar\n* [[Norman Lebrecht]] (born 1948) - British commentator on music and cultural affairs, and novelist\n* [[Tzipi Livni]] - Israeli lawyer and politician, head of the Opposition from 2009-2012. Former Minister of Justice and in charge of negotiations with the Palestinians\n* [[Gadeer Mreeh]] (born 1984) - first [[Druze]] woman to become a member of the [[Knesset]]\n* [[Avi Weinroth]] - Lawyer represents corporations in Israel and governmental companies.\n\n==Notable faculty==\n{{see also|Category:Bar-Ilan University faculty}}\n\n{{div col}}\n* [[Doron Aurbach]]\n* [[Nathan Aviezer]]\n* [[Moshe Bar (neuroscientist)|Moshe Bar]]\n* [[Avi Bell]]\n*[[Pinkhos Churgin]] \n* [[Cyril Domb]]\n* [[Shlomo Eckstein]]\n* [[Adam Ferziger]]\n* [[Jonathan Fox (professor of politics)|Jonathan Fox]]\n* [[Hillel Furstenberg]]\n* [[Ruth Halperin-Kaddari]]\n* [[Oren Harman]]\n* [[Shlomo Havlin]]\n* [[Arye L. Hillman]]\n* [[Max Jammer]]\n* [[Efraim Karsh]]\n* [[Mordechai Kedar]]\n* [[Sarit Kraus]]\n* [[Ernest Krausz]]\n* [[Baruch Kurzweil]]\n* [[Aren Maeir]]\n* [[Arie Reich]]\n* [[Mary Schaps]]\n* [[Daniel Sperber]]\n* [[Avraham Trahtman]]\n* [[Zeev Zalevsky]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Israel]]\n* [[Ashkelon Academic College]]\n* [[Jerusalem College of Technology]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.biu.ac.il/index_eng.shtml}}\n* [http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=980&pt=1&pid=35&level=3&cPath=35,980 BIU History]\n* [http://www1.biu.ac.il/indexE.php?id=90&pt=4&pid=30&level=2&cPath=90 Bar-Ilan University \u2013 Study Programs for Olim/Foreign Students]\n* [http://www.judaismshop.com/Bar-Ilan-Responsa/ Bar-Ilan responsa website]\n* [http://medicine.biu.ac.il/en Bar-Ilan Faculty of Medicine]\n* [http://nano.biu.ac.il/ Bar-Ilan Institute of Nanotechnology and Advanced Materials (BINA)]\n* [http://law.biu.ac.il/en Bar-Ilan Faculty of Law]\n* {{in lang|he}} [http://www.bis.org.il Bar-Ilan Students Union]\n* {{in lang|es}} [http://www.alubi.org Amigos Latinoamericanos de la Universidad de Bar Ilan]\n\n{{Universities in Israel}}\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Religious Zionism}}\n\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University| ]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1955]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ramat Gan]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Israel]]\n[[Category:Universities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Education in Tel Aviv District]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bar-Ilan_University"}
{"title_page": "Green Tree Estates water crisis", "text_new": "== '''Overview''' ==\n\nThe Green Tree Estates is a low-income mobile home neighborhood with an estimated 50 residents currently living on the property. The city of [[Denton, Texas|Denton]] annexed the neighborhood in 2011, but the land remained as private property. Landowner, Don Roddy, was supposed to install infrastructure to connect to the City of Denton's water supply but never followed through. The residents living on the Green Tree Estates property rely on the privately-owned well for water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/some-city-of-denton-taxpayers-are-days-away-from-losing-water-service/287-03f9e413-0001-4a7d-817e-4fd906d0c87f|title=Some city of Denton taxpayers are days away from losing water service|website=WFAA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\nDespite numerous fines for failing to bring their system into compliance, Roddy has cut off the water supply completely. As a private owner, Roddy is within his rights to do so but has not gone on record to explain his decision <ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> <ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref>. On November 13, 2019, Denton Mayor Chris Watts issued a declaration of local state of disaster for the Green Tree Estates neighborhood<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-declares-disaster-for-green-tree-estates/article_eb37b512-6dbb-5665-a454-714907663225.html</ref> and two days later, the City of Denton began sending tanks of nonpotable water to Green Tree Estates.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/resident-hopes-city-will-extend-green-tree-estates-emergency-declaration/article_fa527a91-2f5c-52a3-aad5-64d790801e61.html</ref> Discussions on extending nearby water mains for the homes to connect to have been proposed at city council meetings. However, this idea is currently on hold due to (1) concerns that many residents living at Green Tree estates will not be able to afford the fees required by the contractors, (2) questions regarding which homes are up to code, and (3) concerns on the quality, age, and structural integrity of the private water system. \u201cDenton city council plans to revisit the issue April 21, to give residents and city officials time to see which owners would be able to connect if the water main.\u201d<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref><ref>https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2019/11/14/mayor-of-denton-declares-state-of-emergency-for-mobile-home-community/</ref> \n== '''Timeline''' ==\n===== 2019 =====\n* October 29 \u2013 A neighborhood meeting takes place to inform the Green Tree Estates residents of the situation and to collect feedback. However, the majority of the residents are Hispanic and few speak English. No translator is present at the meeting which results in most residents leaving more confused than before.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html.</ref> In the meeting, Denton director of utilities, Ken Banks, estimates that bringing in a modern water system to the neighborhood would exceed $500,000. A representative from the Public Utility Commission informs that the city is not in a position to enforce Roddy to keep the water system on any longer.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/water-options-running-low-for-small-mobile-home-neighborhood/article_555c6e97-92d0-5d37-b237-3c2c55167ef9.html</ref> \n* November 11 \u2013 A second neighborhood meeting takes place to discuss next steps. City Manager, Todd Hileman, discusses how declaring the situation as an emergency would allow for temporary funding to ease the situation until a more permanent plan could be put into action. A translator is also present at this meeting to convey information to the Green Tree Estates residents.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-city-council-could-declare-emergency-for-residents-of-green-tree-estates/article_82aa8360-d6b9-54b2-92fb-16f5426e38d3.html</ref> \n* November 13 \u2013 Denton Mayor Chris Watts issues a declaration of local state of disaster for the Green Tree Estates neighborhood.<ref>https://www.cityofdenton.com/CoD/media/City-of-Denton/News%20and%20Events/Press%20Releases/Declaration-of-Disaster-Green-Tree-Estates-Subdivision.pdf</ref> <ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-declares-disaster-for-green-tree-estates/article_eb37b512-6dbb-5665-a454-714907663225.html</ref>\n* November 14 \u2013 The City of Denton delivers 55-gallon barrels for the residents to fill up before water turns off. Water is such poor quality that these drums are rendered useless.\n* November 15 \u2013 Owner and well operator of Green Tree Estates, Don Roddy, turns off private well water.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/humanitarian-crisis-denton-leaders-vote-to-extend-emergency-declaration-over-neighborhoods-water-woes/287-d5dc9836-e6da-4fff-9fd5-cbd047bfedbd</ref>\n* November 15 \u2013 A special city council meeting is held to discuss how emergency funds will be spent. Denton decides to purchase 14 275-gallon tanks to fill with non-potable water and distribute them to families of the Green Tree Estates. The city also plans to refill the tanks three days a week.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/resident-hopes-city-will-extend-green-tree-estates-emergency-declaration/article_fa527a91-2f5c-52a3-aad5-64d790801e61.html</ref>\n* December 10 \u2013 The Denton City Council agrees to extend an emergency declaration over water service to the Green Tree Estates until February. In the meantime, plans to conduct courtesy home inspections and collect a census on property owners and tenants are made and considered \u201ckey\u201d to settling on a long-term solution.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-to-extend-emergency-declaration-for-green-tree-through-may/article_eacda077-f51e-51a0-b245-bb3e56b2c0f1.html</ref>\n===== 2020 =====\n* February 4 \u2013 An attorney representing the Green Tree Estates neighborhood advises the residents to hire their own inspectors, resulting in none of the 14 homes accepting courtesy inspections from the city of Denton. The residents are seeking to calculate the total costs before deciding to connect to Denton\u2019s water system which means they need more time for the assessments and work. The residents of Green Tree Estates are asking the city of Denton for an extension on the public emergency until May 2021.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-continues-to-work-with-green-tree-residents-on-water-issue/article_e8e7f6d9-39eb-5587-8457-985fe57d47aa.html</ref>\n* February 18 \u2013 Denton \u201ccity council plans to revisit the issue April 21, to give residents and city officials time to see which owners would be able to connect if the water main.\u201d<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref>\n== '''Background''' ==\nThe Green Tree Estates neighborhood had been considered an unincorporated community for several decades before being annexed by the city of Denton, Texas in 2011. This means that before becoming Denton citizens, the \u201cresidents had virtually no access to municipal services (i.e., garbage, sanitation, fire protection, street repair, lights, water utilities, etc.)\u201d<ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> With a history of neglected basic public services, residents of the Green Tree Estates have not felt as if they have a voice in their community. Even after being annexed by the city of Denton, \u201cthe water remains undrinkable, and other municipal services have failed to materialize.\u201d<ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> Around October of 2019, system owner, Don Roddy, made plans to cut the community\u2019s water system without giving the appropriate 120-day notification as required by the Texas Public Utilities Commission. <ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> Roddy denied Denton City Council\u2019s request to keep the water system going until a resolution was found. The city then reached out to the Public Utility Commission and requested the PUC enforce the full 120-day notice.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/water-options-running-low-for-small-mobile-home-neighborhood/article_555c6e97-92d0-5d37-b237-3c2c55167ef9.html</ref> In the first neighborhood meeting to address the issue, Denton\u2019s director of utilities, Ken Banks, estimated that bringing in a modern water system to the neighborhood would exceed $500,000. An attending representative sent from the PUC maintained that the city could not enforce a longer notice, but declined to make any further public statement. Furthermore, \u201cthe Public Utility Commission would not accept the city\u2019s evidence that the well was a retail utility and thus subject to the longer notice.\u201d<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/water-options-running-low-for-small-mobile-home-neighborhood/article_555c6e97-92d0-5d37-b237-3c2c55167ef9.html</ref> <ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-to-declare-public-emergency-for-green-tree-water-supply/article_183fc397-f58d-5231-9798-b573c66a4182.html</ref> It was later reported that Roddy had reached out to the Texas Commission of Environmental Quality and reported some of the connections were illegal, allowing Roddy to disconnect service at any time.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref> A second neighborhood meeting was held two weeks later to discuss next steps. City Manager, Todd Hileman, discussed how declaring the situation as an emergency would allow for temporary funding to ease the situation until a more permanent plan could be put into action. A translator was present at this meeting to convey information to the Green Tree Estates residents. The residents disagreed with other temporary city plans to alleviate the issue, including the idea to bring in portable toilets and a central community shower trailer.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-city-council-could-declare-emergency-for-residents-of-green-tree-estates/article_82aa8360-d6b9-54b2-92fb-16f5426e38d3.html</ref> The residents expressed that as tax-paying citizens, they were seeking equitable benefits that any other Denton resident would receive. Deputy City Manager, Mario Canizares, recognized that the residents had \u201cno problem paying. It\u2019s just getting the water there that\u2019s the problem.\u201d Other council members addressed concerns about the legality of some of the solutions posed, as well as concerns regarding the plumbing and electrical work being too difficult to install in the mobile homes.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-to-declare-public-emergency-for-green-tree-water-supply/article_183fc397-f58d-5231-9798-b573c66a4182.html</ref> \n\nOn November 13, 2019, Denton Mayor, Chris Watts, issued a declaration of a local state of disaster for the Green Tree Estates neighborhood before the water service would be discontinued. This allowed for 90-day temporary funding for the Green Tree Estates residents.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-declares-disaster-for-green-tree-estates/article_eb37b512-6dbb-5665-a454-714907663225.html</ref> The next day, the city of Denton delivered 55-gallon barrels for the residents to fill up before their water was turned off. However, the existing water was such poor quality that these drums were considered useless by any resident who did not have access to a filter.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/a-small-community-in-denton-braces-to-lose-water-friday/287-eb0dee86-f9ea-4ba0-8809-113b0756315c</ref> The following day a special city council meeting was scheduled to discuss next steps. It was decided that the city would supply the community with 14 275-gallon tanks filled with non-potable water. The city also made plans to refill the containers regularly. Green Tree Estates residents expressed their concerns that this was not going to be enough water to support their entire families.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-votes-to-provide-temporary-water-services-to-green-tree-estates-for-90-days/article_1d3ba7f2-c13f-5b85-8f29-ed0d267600bd.htm</ref> On December 10, 2019, \u201cthe Denton City Council agreed to extend an emergency declaration over water service to the Green Tree Estates until school lets out in May.\u201d Around this same time, \u201ca housing advocacy group threatened to file a fair housing complaint with the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development on behalf of Green Tree Estates.\u201d The group's coordinator ultimately decided to put a hold on filing the complaint due to the city's decision to extend the emergency declaration. While long-term plans had been discussed, costs were a concern for both residents and city council members. It was decided that commitment towards a long-term solution would be made in February 2020. City leaders asked for the cooperation from the Green Tree Estates residents regarding conducting home inspections as well as helping to identify which residents owned their properties and which were tenants. Through these actions, \u201cadvocacy groups and the city of Denton could work together on the needed easements for new water lines.\u201d City manager, Todd Hileman, claimed that the city\u2019s ability to get those easements was \u201ckey\u201d to settling on a long-term solution. However, residents of the Green Tree Estates expressed confusion stating that they didn\u2019t understand what was being asked of them.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-to-extend-emergency-declaration-for-green-tree-through-may/article_eacda077-f51e-51a0-b245-bb3e56b2c0f1.html</ref> \n\nBy February 4, 2020, none of the 14 families living in the Green Tree Estates had completed the courtesy inspections of their homes from the city of Denton. Instead, the neighborhood\u2019s attorney recommended the residents bring in their own inspectors. A Univision television reporter reported that \u201cthe residents want to calculate the total costs before deciding to connect to the system.\u201d Lastly, the residents told the deputy director of public affairs that they needed more time for the assessments and the work and asked the city council to extend the public emergency until May 2021. Some council members were uneasy with the request for the extension to continue for more than a year, but other members were more comfortable with it as long as progress is shown to be made.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-continues-to-work-with-green-tree-residents-on-water-issue/article_e8e7f6d9-39eb-5587-8457-985fe57d47aa.html</ref> It was decided at a later meeting that council would revisit the issue on April 21 to assess which the residents can connect to Denton\u2019s main water system.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref> \n== '''Outside organizational contributions''' ==\n\u201c[[Habitat for Humanity]] of Denton County is stepping in to help residents look for ways to pay for the installation and help the city with the logistics.\u201d<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref> [[League of United Latin American Citizens]](LULAC) is an organization that seeks to advance the economic condition, educational attainment, political influence, housing, health and civil rights of Hispanic Americans through community-based programs.<ref>https://lulac.org/about/</ref> LULAC has been organizing ways to help the community and make sure their needs are met. They have been serving as translators during meetings to disseminate information to the residents.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref> LULAC has listed an email that directly connects citizens who want to help support the community. Movimiento Cosecha Denton is a nonviolent movement who utilizes strikes and boycotts in fighting for permanent protection, dignity, and respect for the undocumented immigrant population living in the United States.<ref>https://www.lahuelga.com/about</ref>\n== '''Media Responses''' ==\n* On November 12, 2019, NBC DFW reported the neglect towards the Green Tree Estates community due to the legal gray area that the City of Denton calls a \"private civil matter.\"<ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/water-crisis-looming-for-residents-of-denton-neighborhood/2129947/</ref>\n* On November 13 and 14, 2019, CBS DFW and NBC DFW reported the Mayor of Denton\u2019s declaration of state of emergency and subsequent efforts to provide temporary water and water storage containers to the residents.<ref>https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2019/11/14/mayor-of-denton-declares-state-of-emergency-for-mobile-home-community/</ref> <ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/mayor-declares-disaster-for-denton-neighborhood/2149792/</ref>\n* On November 14, 2019, WFAA reported the Green Tree Estates looming water cutoff, as well as the poor quality of water the residents had been receiving up until that point. The report also documents the neighbor's insufficient amount of emergency water.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/a-small-community-in-denton-braces-to-lose-water-friday/287-eb0dee86-f9ea-4ba0-8809-113b0756315c</ref>\n* On November 15, 2019, NBC DFW and WFAA reported the official shutoff of the water supply to the Green Tree Estates as well as Denton\u2019s plan to extend the emergency declaration.<ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/denton-community-water-service-set-to-be-cut-off/2193536/</ref> <ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/humanitarian-crisis-denton-leaders-vote-to-extend-emergency-declaration-over-neighborhoods-water-woes/287-d5dc9836-e6da-4fff-9fd5-cbd047bfedbd</ref>\n* On November 29, 2019, Liberation News published an article that gives an insight on how unincorporated communities are mishandled and gives a brief history of the Green Tree Estates.<ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref>\n* On February 19, 2020, WFAA reported how the Green Tree Estates residents are continuing to wait on a permanent solution.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref>\n* The Denton Record-Chronicle has been a valuable source for coverage regarding the Green Tree Estates water crisis.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/water-woes-at-green-tree-estates/collection_7b5ed231-2ddc-5064-b463-7754d392a780.html</ref>\n== Private Water ==\nProviding a source of clean water to the residents of the Green Tree Estates is critical for the overall quality of life. The residents have expressed concerns about their water quality for years. The murky yellow, orange, and brown water has been reported to cause sores and blisters on the bodies of children that come into contact with it.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref> <ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "== '''Overview''' ==\n\nThe Green Tree Estates is a low-income mobile home neighborhood with an estimated 50 residents currently living on the property. The city of [[Denton, Texas|Denton]] annexed the neighborhood in 2011, but the land remained as private property. Landowner, Don Roddy, was supposed to install infrastructure to connect to the City of Denton's water supply but never followed through. The residents living on the Green Tree Estates property rely on the privately-owned well for water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/some-city-of-denton-taxpayers-are-days-away-from-losing-water-service/287-03f9e413-0001-4a7d-817e-4fd906d0c87f|title=Some city of Denton taxpayers are days away from losing water service|website=WFAA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\nDespite numerous fines for failing to bring their system into compliance, Roddy has cut off the water supply completely. As a private owner, Roddy is within his rights to do so but has not gone on record to explain his decision <ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> <ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref>. On November 13, 2019, Denton Mayor Chris Watts issued a declaration of local state of disaster for the Green Tree Estates neighborhood<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-declares-disaster-for-green-tree-estates/article_eb37b512-6dbb-5665-a454-714907663225.html</ref> and two days later, the City of Denton began sending tanks of nonpotable water to Green Tree Estates.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/resident-hopes-city-will-extend-green-tree-estates-emergency-declaration/article_fa527a91-2f5c-52a3-aad5-64d790801e61.html</ref> Discussions on extending nearby water mains for the homes to connect to have been proposed at city council meetings. However, this idea is currently on hold due to (1) concerns that many residents living at Green Tree estates will not be able to afford the fees required by the contractors, (2) questions regarding which homes are up to code, and (3) concerns on the quality, age, and structural integrity of the private water system. \u201cDenton city council plans to revisit the issue April 21, to give residents and city officials time to see which owners would be able to connect if the water main.\u201d<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref><ref>https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2019/11/14/mayor-of-denton-declares-state-of-emergency-for-mobile-home-community/</ref> \n== '''Timeline''' ==\n===== 2019 =====\n* October 29 \u2013 A neighborhood meeting takes place to inform the Green Tree Estates residents of the situation and to collect feedback. However, the majority of the residents are Hispanic and few speak English. No translator is present at the meeting which results in most residents leaving more confused than before.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html.</ref> In the meeting, Denton director of utilities, Ken Banks, estimates that bringing in a modern water system to the neighborhood would exceed $500,000. A representative from the Public Utility Commission informs that the city is not in a position to enforce Roddy to keep the water system on any longer.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/water-options-running-low-for-small-mobile-home-neighborhood/article_555c6e97-92d0-5d37-b237-3c2c55167ef9.html</ref> \n* November 11 \u2013 A second neighborhood meeting takes place to discuss next steps. City Manager, Todd Hileman, discusses how declaring the situation as an emergency would allow for temporary funding to ease the situation until a more permanent plan could be put into action. A translator is also present at this meeting to convey information to the Green Tree Estates residents.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-city-council-could-declare-emergency-for-residents-of-green-tree-estates/article_82aa8360-d6b9-54b2-92fb-16f5426e38d3.html</ref> \n* November 13 \u2013 Denton Mayor Chris Watts issues a declaration of local state of disaster for the Green Tree Estates neighborhood.<ref>https://www.cityofdenton.com/CoD/media/City-of-Denton/News%20and%20Events/Press%20Releases/Declaration-of-Disaster-Green-Tree-Estates-Subdivision.pdf</ref> <ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-declares-disaster-for-green-tree-estates/article_eb37b512-6dbb-5665-a454-714907663225.html</ref>\n* November 14 \u2013 The City of Denton delivers 55-gallon barrels for the residents to fill up before water turns off. Water is such poor quality that these drums are rendered useless.\n* November 15 \u2013 Owner and well operator of Green Tree Estates, Don Roddy, turns off private well water.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/humanitarian-crisis-denton-leaders-vote-to-extend-emergency-declaration-over-neighborhoods-water-woes/287-d5dc9836-e6da-4fff-9fd5-cbd047bfedbd</ref>\n* November 15 \u2013 A special city council meeting is held to discuss how emergency funds will be spent. Denton decides to purchase 14 275-gallon tanks to fill with non-potable water and distribute them to families of the Green Tree Estates. The city also plans to refill the tanks three days a week.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/resident-hopes-city-will-extend-green-tree-estates-emergency-declaration/article_fa527a91-2f5c-52a3-aad5-64d790801e61.html</ref>\n* December 10 \u2013 The Denton City Council agrees to extend an emergency declaration over water service to the Green Tree Estates until February. In the meantime, plans to conduct courtesy home inspections and collect a census on property owners and tenants are made and considered \u201ckey\u201d to settling on a long-term solution.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-to-extend-emergency-declaration-for-green-tree-through-may/article_eacda077-f51e-51a0-b245-bb3e56b2c0f1.html</ref>\n===== 2020 =====\n* February 4 \u2013 An attorney representing the Green Tree Estates neighborhood advises the residents to hire their own inspectors, resulting in none of the 14 homes accepting courtesy inspections from the city of Denton. The residents are seeking to calculate the total costs before deciding to connect to Denton\u2019s water system which means they need more time for the assessments and work. The residents of Green Tree Estates are asking the city of Denton for an extension on the public emergency until May 2021.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-continues-to-work-with-green-tree-residents-on-water-issue/article_e8e7f6d9-39eb-5587-8457-985fe57d47aa.html</ref>\n* February 18 \u2013 Denton \u201ccity council plans to revisit the issue April 21, to give residents and city officials time to see which owners would be able to connect if the water main.\u201d<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref>\n== '''Background''' ==\nThe Green Tree Estates neighborhood had been considered an unincorporated community for several decades before being annexed by the city of Denton, Texas in 2011. This means that before becoming Denton citizens, the \u201cresidents had virtually no access to municipal services (i.e., garbage, sanitation, fire protection, street repair, lights, water utilities, etc.)\u201d<ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> With a history of neglection to basic public services, residents of the Green Tree Estates have not felt as if they have a voice in their community. Even after being annexed by the city of Denton, \u201cthe water remains undrinkable, and other municipal services have failed to materialize.\u201d<ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> Around October of 2019, system owner, Don Roddy, made plans to cut the community\u2019s water system without giving the appropriate 120-day notification as required by the Texas Public Utilities Commission. <ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref> Roddy denied Denton City Council\u2019s request to keep the water system going until a resolution was found. The city then reached out to the Public Utility Commission and requested the PUC enforce the full 120-day notice.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/water-options-running-low-for-small-mobile-home-neighborhood/article_555c6e97-92d0-5d37-b237-3c2c55167ef9.html</ref> In the first neighborhood meeting to address the issue, Denton\u2019s director of utilities, Ken Banks, estimated that bringing in a modern water system to the neighborhood would exceed $500,000. An attending representative sent from the PUC maintained that the city could not enforce a longer notice, but declined to make any further public statement. Furthermore, \u201cthe Public Utility Commission would not accept the city\u2019s evidence that the well was a retail utility and thus subject to the longer notice.\u201d<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/water-options-running-low-for-small-mobile-home-neighborhood/article_555c6e97-92d0-5d37-b237-3c2c55167ef9.html</ref> <ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-to-declare-public-emergency-for-green-tree-water-supply/article_183fc397-f58d-5231-9798-b573c66a4182.html</ref> It was later reported that Roddy had reached out to the Texas Commission of Environmental Quality and reported some of the connections were illegal, allowing Roddy to disconnect service at any time.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref> A second neighborhood meeting was held two weeks later to discuss next steps. City Manager, Todd Hileman, discussed how declaring the situation as an emergency would allow for temporary funding to ease the situation until a more permanent plan could be put into action. A translator was present at this meeting to convey information to the Green Tree Estates residents. The residents disagreed with other temporary city plans to alleviate the issue, including the idea to bring in portable toilets and a central community shower trailer.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-city-council-could-declare-emergency-for-residents-of-green-tree-estates/article_82aa8360-d6b9-54b2-92fb-16f5426e38d3.html</ref> The residents expressed that as tax-paying citizens, they were seeking equitable benefits that any other Denton resident would receive. Deputy City Manager, Mario Canizares, recognized that the residents had \u201cno problem paying. It\u2019s just getting the water there that\u2019s the problem.\u201d Other council members addressed concerns about the legality of some of the solutions posed, as well as concerns regarding the plumbing and electrical work being too difficult to install in the mobile homes.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-to-declare-public-emergency-for-green-tree-water-supply/article_183fc397-f58d-5231-9798-b573c66a4182.html</ref> \n\nOn November 13, 2019, Denton Mayor, Chris Watts, issued a declaration of a local state of disaster for the Green Tree Estates neighborhood before the water service would be discontinued. This allowed for 90-day temporary funding for the Green Tree Estates residents.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/mayor-declares-disaster-for-green-tree-estates/article_eb37b512-6dbb-5665-a454-714907663225.html</ref> The next day, the city of Denton delivered 55-gallon barrels for the residents to fill up before their water was turned off. However, the existing water was such poor quality that these drums were considered useless by any resident who did not have access to a filter.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/a-small-community-in-denton-braces-to-lose-water-friday/287-eb0dee86-f9ea-4ba0-8809-113b0756315c</ref> The following day a special city council meeting was scheduled to discuss next steps. It was decided that the city would supply the community with 14 275-gallon tanks filled with non-potable water. The city also made plans to refill the containers regularly. Green Tree Estates residents expressed their concerns that this was not going to be enough water to support their entire families.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-votes-to-provide-temporary-water-services-to-green-tree-estates-for-90-days/article_1d3ba7f2-c13f-5b85-8f29-ed0d267600bd.htm</ref> On December 10, 2019, \u201cthe Denton City Council agreed to extend an emergency declaration over water service to the Green Tree Estates until school lets out in May.\u201d Around this same time, \u201ca housing advocacy group threatened to file a fair housing complaint with the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development on behalf of Green Tree Estates.\u201d The group's coordinator ultimately decided to put a hold on filing the complaint due to the city's decision to extend the emergency declaration. While long-term plans had been discussed, costs were a concern for both residents and city council members. It was decided that commitment towards a long-term solution would be made in February 2020. City leaders asked for the cooperation from the Green Tree Estates residents regarding conducting home inspections as well as helping to identify which residents owned their properties and which were tenants. Through these actions, \u201cadvocacy groups and the city of Denton could work together on the needed easements for new water lines.\u201d City manager, Todd Hileman, claimed that the city\u2019s ability to get those easements was \u201ckey\u201d to settling on a long-term solution. However, residents of the Green Tree Estates expressed confusion stating that they didn\u2019t understand what was being asked of them.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-to-extend-emergency-declaration-for-green-tree-through-may/article_eacda077-f51e-51a0-b245-bb3e56b2c0f1.html</ref> \n\nBy February 4, 2020, none of the 14 families living in the Green Tree Estates had completed the courtesy inspections of their homes from the city of Denton. Instead, the neighborhood\u2019s attorney recommended the residents bring in their own inspectors. A Univision television reporter reported that \u201cthe residents want to calculate the total costs before deciding to connect to the system.\u201d Lastly, the residents told the deputy director of public affairs that they needed more time for the assessments and the work and asked the city council to extend the public emergency until May 2021. Some council members were uneasy with the request for the extension to continue for more than a year, but other members were more comfortable with it as long as progress is shown to be made.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton-continues-to-work-with-green-tree-residents-on-water-issue/article_e8e7f6d9-39eb-5587-8457-985fe57d47aa.html</ref> It was decided at a later meeting that council would revisit the issue on April 21 to assess which the residents can connect to Denton\u2019s main water system.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref> \n== '''Outside organizational contributions''' ==\n\u201cHabitat for Humanity of Denton County is stepping in to help residents look for ways to pay for the installation and help the city with the logistics.\u201d<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref> League of United Latin American Citizens(LULAC) is an organization that seeks to advance the economic condition, educational attainment, political influence, housing, health and civil rights of Hispanic Americans through community-based programs.<ref>https://lulac.org/about/</ref> LULAC has been organizing ways to help the community and make sure their needs are met. They have been serving as translators during meetings to disseminate information to the residents.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref> LULAC has listed an email that directly connects citizens who want to help support the community. Movimiento Cosecha Denton is a nonviolent movement who utilizes strikes and boycotts in fighting for permanent protection, dignity, and respect for the undocumented immigrant population living in the United States.<ref>https://www.lahuelga.com/about</ref>\n== '''Media Responses''' ==\n* On November 12, 2019, NBC DFW reported the neglect towards the Green Tree Estates community due to the legal gray area that the City of Denton calls a \"private civil matter.\"<ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/water-crisis-looming-for-residents-of-denton-neighborhood/2129947/</ref>\n* On November 13 and 14, 2019, CBS DFW and NBC DFW reported the Mayor of Denton\u2019s declaration of state of emergency and subsequent efforts to provide temporary water and water storage containers to the residents.<ref>https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2019/11/14/mayor-of-denton-declares-state-of-emergency-for-mobile-home-community/</ref> <ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/mayor-declares-disaster-for-denton-neighborhood/2149792/</ref>\n* On November 14, 2019, WFAA reported the Green Tree Estates looming water cutoff, as well as the poor quality of water the residents had been receiving up until that point. The report also documents the neighbor's insufficient amount of emergency water.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/a-small-community-in-denton-braces-to-lose-water-friday/287-eb0dee86-f9ea-4ba0-8809-113b0756315c</ref>\n* On November 15, 2019, NBC DFW and WFAA reported the official shutoff of the water supply to the Green Tree Estates as well as Denton\u2019s plan to extend the emergency declaration.<ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/denton-community-water-service-set-to-be-cut-off/2193536/</ref> <ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/local/denton-county/humanitarian-crisis-denton-leaders-vote-to-extend-emergency-declaration-over-neighborhoods-water-woes/287-d5dc9836-e6da-4fff-9fd5-cbd047bfedbd</ref>\n* On November 29, 2019, Liberation News published an article that gives an insight on how unincorporated communities are mishandled and gives a brief history of the Green Tree Estates.<ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref>\n* On February 19, 2020, WFAA reported how the Green Tree Estates residents are continuing to wait on a permanent solution.<ref>https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/for-neighbors-with-serious-water-worries-the-future-is-unclear/287-d0e45259-d986-48c0-98d1-4bdfc33fbac5</ref>\n* The Denton Record-Chronicle has been a valuable source for coverage regarding the Green Tree Estates water crisis.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/water-woes-at-green-tree-estates/collection_7b5ed231-2ddc-5064-b463-7754d392a780.html</ref>\n== Private Water ==\nProviding a source of clean water to the residents of the Green Tree Estates is critical for the overall quality of life. The residents have expressed concerns about their water quality for years. The murky yellow, orange, and brown water has been reported to cause sores and blisters on the bodies of children that come into contact with it.<ref>https://dentonrc.com/news/denton/small-denton-neighborhood-seeks-viable-water-options-as-they-prepare-to-lose-current-service/article_d26a6601-c96a-5620-939c-a9d0c3063953.html</ref> <ref>https://www.liberationnews.org/this-neighborhood-in-denton-has-had-poisoned-water-for-decades-now-theyre-fighting-back/</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Kdewolff", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Tree_Estates_water_crisis"}
{"title_page": "List of spouses of Prime Ministers of Thailand", "text_new": "{{Infobox Political post\n |post            = Spouse of the Prime Minister of Thailand\n |body            = \n |style           = \n |image           = President Benigno S. Aquino III witnessed as His Excellency General Prayut Chan-o-cha 28-08-2015 cropped 1.jpg\n |incumbent       = Naraporn Chan-o-cha\n |incumbentsince  = 24 August 2014\n |residence       = \n |formation       = 28 June 1932\n |inaugural       = Choei Hutasingha\n |website         = \n}}\n\nThe '''spouse of the Prime Minister of Thailand''' ({{lang-th|\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e23\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e21\u0e19\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22}}) is the wife or husband of the [[Prime Minister of Thailand]].\n\nThe spouse of the current Prime Minister is Associate Professor Naraporn Chan-o-cha.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/politics/First-family-keeps-low-profile-30241498.html|title=First family keeps low profile|author=|date=August 22, 2014|work= |newspaper= The Nation |accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== List ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!\n! Spouse\n! Maiden name\n! Tenure began\n! Tenure ended\n! Prime Minister\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1\n| Choei Hutasingha<br>{{lang|th|\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e22 \u0e2b\u0e38\u0e15\u0e30\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e4c}}\n| ''Unknown''\n| 28 June 1932\n| 20 June 1933\n| [[Phraya Manopakorn Nititada]] (Kon Hutasingha)\n|\n|-\n| 2\n| ''Khunying'' Phit Phahonphonphayuhasena<br>{{lang|th|\u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e2b\u0e0d\u0e34\u0e07\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e08 \u0e1e\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e1e\u0e25\u0e1e\u0e22\u0e38\u0e2b\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32}}<ref>{{cite journal|journal= Royal Thai Government Gazette |volume= 55 |issue= 0\u0e07 |pages= 3021 |script-title=th:\u0e41\u0e08\u0e49\u0e07\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e33\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e19\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e21\u0e19\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35 \u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0